    <item>
      <title>Using PyCall with uv-managed Python Environments</title>
      <link>https://yuan-ru-lin.github.io/blog/pycall-with-uv/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://yuan-ru-lin.github.io/blog/pycall-with-uv/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-problem&#34;&gt;The Problem &lt;a href=&#34;#the-problem&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;ğŸ”—&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;When using PyCall.jl with Python executables and packages managed by &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/astral-sh/uv&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;uv&lt;/a&gt;, PyCall can find the Python executable in the virtual environment but doesn&amp;rsquo;t recognize packages installed via &lt;code&gt;uv add&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-solution&#34;&gt;The Solution &lt;a href=&#34;#the-solution&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;ğŸ”—&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Add the uv virtual environment&amp;rsquo;s site-packages to Python&amp;rsquo;s path before importing packages:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-julia&#34; data-lang=&#34;julia&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;pushfirst!(pyimport(&lt;span style=&#34;color:#e6db74&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;sys&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;)&lt;span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#e6db74&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;path&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;, realpath(&lt;span style=&#34;color:#e6db74&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;.venv/lib/python3.11/site-packages/&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;))&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;This prepends the uv virtual environment&amp;rsquo;s package directory to Python&amp;rsquo;s module search path, allowing PyCall to find all packages installed via uv.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Note:&lt;/strong&gt; Adjust the Python version in the path (&lt;code&gt;python3.11&lt;/code&gt;) to match your virtual environment&amp;rsquo;s Python version.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
